#let images = (
  "4.1": (
    caption: [The warming effect of the sun is greatest at the equator. The sun’s position in the middle of the day varies from directly overhead in the tropics to near the horizon in polar regions.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-10-53-23.png"
  ),
  "4.2": (
    caption: [The tilt of the earth’s axis causes seasonal variation in climate. The orientation of the earth’s axis relative to the sun, and thus the incident solar radiation at each latitude, changes as the earth orbits the sun. The position of the solar equator also changes with the seasons.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-10-53-49.png"
  ),
  "4.3": (
    caption: [Annual temperature variation is greatest at high latitudes in the Northern Hemisphere. Mean monthly temperatures vary more over the year in the Northern hemisphere because the moderating influence of water is less there.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-10-54-17.png"
  ),
  "4.4": (
    caption: [The equilibrium vapor pressure of water increases with temperature. Warm air can hold more water vapor than cold air.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-10-54-54.png"
  ),
  "4.5": (
    caption: [Differential warming of the earth’s surface creates Hadley circulation. Warm, moist air rises in the tropics, and cool, dry air moves toward the tropics from subtropical latitudes to replace it, forming Hadley cells. This circulation pattern drives the secondary Ferrel cells and polar cells at higher latitudes.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-10-55-56.png"
  ),
  "4.6": (
    caption: [The Coriolis effect causes air currents to veer to the right in the Northern Hemisphere and to the left in the Southern Hemisphere. It results in the prevailing surface wind patterns known as the trade winds and the westerlies.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-10-58-02.png"
  ),
  "4.7": (
    caption: [The distribution of the earth’s major deserts and humid areas is established by Hadley circulation.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-10-58-33.png"
  ),
  "4.8": (
    caption: [The major ocean surface currents are driven by winds and the earth’s rotation.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-10-59-11.png"
  ),
  "4.9": (
    caption: [Upwelling currents often support high biological productivity. The Benguela Current off the western coast of South Africa has a zone of upwelling and supports an important fishery. Cape gannets feed on small fish in the adjacent cold, nutrient-rich waters.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-11-00-13.png"
  ),
  "4.10": (
    caption: [The movement of the intertropical convergence affects precipitation patterns. The seasonal latitudinal movement of the solar equator results in two seasons of heavy precipitation at the equator and a single rainy season alternating with a pronounced dry season at the edges of the tropics.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-11-00-33.png"
  ),
"4.11": (
    caption: [Seasonal climatic patterns differ among subtropical localities.
(a) The Chihuahuan Desert in central Mexico has a summer rainy season.
(b) The Sonoran Desert has a combined climatic pattern, with rainfall in summer and winter.
(c) San Diego on the Pacific coast and the Mojave Desert have a winter rain and summer drought (Mediterranean) climatic pattern.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-11-02-01.png"
  ),
  "4.12": (
    caption: [Seasonal changes in the temperature profile of a temperate lake influence vertical mixing of water layers. Vertical mixing is aided by wind-driven currents when the temperature of water is uniform from the surface to the bottom of the lake.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-11-02-37.png"
  ),
  "4.13": (
    caption: [El Niño–Southern Oscillation (ENSO) events result in dramatic climate changes. Sea surface temperatures, ocean thermocline, and wind patterns during normal conditions in the Pacific, and during an ENSO event. ENSO events are marked by large positive anomalies in the multivariate ENSO index.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-11-03-12.png"
  ),
"4.14": (
    caption: [ENSO events have far-reaching effects.
(a) Deviations from the long-term average in rainfall and corn production in Zimbabwe are correlated with sea surface temperature anomalies in the eastern equatorial Pacific Ocean. In this graph, El Niño conditions are indicated by below-average values.
(b) Areas affected by ENSO events from December through February in a typical ENSO year. Zimbabwe is located in the yellow area in southern Africa.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-11-12-52.png"
  ),
"4.15": (
    caption: [Variations in marine temperatures are recorded by foraminifera in deep-sea sediments.
Main graph: Variations in the proportions of oxygen isotopes incorporated into the shells of foraminifera in sediments from the North Atlantic Ocean during the last 500,000 years. The d18O value becomes more negative as the temperature of the water in which the foraminifera lived decreases. The record clearly shows five warm interglacial periods separated by cold glacial periods.
Inset: Shells of several foraminiferan species.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-11-13-30.png"
  ),
  "4.16": (
    caption: [Mountain ranges influence local precipitation patterns. In the Sierra Nevada of California, the prevailing wind comes from the west across the Central Valley. Moisture-laden air is deflected upward by the mountains, resulting in heavy precipitation on the western slope and arid conditions in the Great Basin.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-12-03-52.png"
  ),
  "4.17": (
    caption: [Trade winds create a rain shadow in Central America. Satellite image of western Panama during the dry season shows heavy forest to the north of the continental divide, where the prevailing winds blow humid air from the Caribbean Sea. The Pacific side is dry, indicated by pasture and dry forest.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-12-04-13.png"
  ),
  "4.18": (
    caption: [Many trees shed their leaves during the dry season. These trees are growing in the rain shadow on the Pacific slope of Panama.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-12-04-36.png"
  ),
  "4.19": (
    caption: [Topography can modify the environment on a local scale. Exposure influences the vegetation growing on slopes of the San Gabriel Mountains, near Los Angeles, California. The cooler north-facing slope supports pine–oak forest, while shrubby, drought-resistant chaparral vegetation grows on the south-facing slope.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-12-04-50.png"
  ),
  "4.20": (
    caption: [Vegetation changes with increasing elevation in the mountains of Arizona. The Lower Sonoran zone supports mostly saguaro cactus and small desert trees. Agave and grasses are conspicuous in the Upper Sonoran zone. At higher elevations, large trees predominate, and in the alpine zone above the tree line, bushes, willows, herbs, and lichens are found.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-12-05-20.png"
  ),
  "4.21": (
    caption: [Soil profiles may show distinct layers, or horizons. Prairie soil from Nebraska is weathered to a depth of about 0.9 m, with distinct O, A, B, and C horizons. Prairie soil from Texas has a thinner A horizon and considerable calcium redeposited at the base of the B horizon and in the C horizon below it.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-12-05-47.png"
  ),
  "4.22": (
    caption: [Weathering is more severe in tropical than in temperate climates. Differential weathering results in differential removal of minerals from granitic parent material in Massachusetts and Guyana.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-12-06-20.png"
  ),
  "4.23": (
    caption: [Podsolized soils have reduced fertility. A 1-meter deep profile of a podsolized soil in northern Michigan shows strong leaching of the A horizon. The light-colored E horizon and the dark-colored B horizon form distinct bands.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-12-13-00.png"
  ),
"4.24": (
    caption: [Lateritic soils have little clay and hold few nutrients.
(a) A fresh road cut in the Amazon basin in Ecuador shows a typical lateritic soil profile.
(b) Notice the roots at the top of the B horizon in a layer of illuviated organic matter.
(c) Highly oxidized and deeply weathered soils are also found in the southeastern United States, as in this eroded area in western Tennessee.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-12-13-48.png"
  ),
"4.25": (
    caption: [Pollen grains from different types of plants have distinctive surface patterns that allow them to be identified.
(a) Callirhoe involucrata (geranium poppy mallow),
(b) Ceanothus americanus (New Jersey tea),
(c) Polygonella americana (small southern jointweed).
Scanning electron micrographs (3500×) depict pollen grains of three subtropical plants from North America.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-12-14-08.png"
  ),
"4.26": (
    caption: [Layers of sediments in lakes preserve the history of environmental change in the surrounding watershed.
Main graph: The content of a sediment core from Lake Kis-Mohos Tó in Hungary shows the replacement of needle-leaved forest by broad-leaved deciduous forest and accompanying changes in soils about 10,000 years ago.
Panel: Relative occurrence of elements and charcoal, and relative occurrence of pollen, over thousands of years before present.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-12-14-32.png"
  ),
  "4.27": (
    caption: [Ferns grow abundantly in recently burned areas. The floor of a recently burned aspen forest in northern Michigan is covered with ferns.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-16-12-14-43.png"
  )
)
